narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Comparative history, material culture, frontiers and cities.
I learned an incredible amount about city planning, city building, and the impact of empires on the architecture of the cities they rule.

I gained knowledge about the formation of the colonial city beginning with the Roman municipae. I began making connections between different colonial cities and their legacies, as well as their continuities and differences.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strengths - very interesting readings. Weaknesses - class participation was low. Rarely did we have discussions or cover all the readings.
I think the course could be improved with more student input in each lecture. I particularly enjoyed when students got to present on cities and trading materials.

The class was stimulating in its lectures and presentations. The readings were excellently chosen and were very informative. I wish the discussions of the readings could be improved. Perhaps posting questions beforehand would prompt better discussions in class.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this course to students who are serious about studying history.

Yes. This is a very interesting course and the readings are some of the best I've read. The professors were approachable and kind. They helped create an open class dynamic that allowed people to freely contribute.
Yes, absolutely. Fascinating material with the ability to have leeway in what you focus on throughout the semester and for the final paper.
